&gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; From: tobemligado &lt;jasbell@...&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Can someone explain a coding situation where a Mock object can not be
&gt; used to solve a test case

This is kind of a vague question.  But I can certainly think of a simple
case where a mock object won&#39;t do, which is if you need to test a method
that creates an object you want to mock, but doesn&#39;t provide a parameter by
which the mock object can be introduced.

Take the example posted yesterday in the &quot;Websphere Connection Pool&quot; thread,
where I suggested passing a mock object implementation of ConnectionFactory
in as a parameter instead of a real ConnectionFactory:

public Object  doMyThing(ConnectionFactory factory, String s)
    Connection con = factory.getConnection();
    // do stuff on the connection
    con.close();
    // and return the object.
    return object;
}

But if you had to test a method that created the ConnectionFactory inside
the method, you couldn&#39;t use a mock object.  You&#39;d have to refactor the
method, or ask whoever owns it to.  :-&gt;

public Object  doMyThing(String s)
    ConnectionFactory factory = getConnectionFactory();
    Connection con = factory.getConnection();
    // do stuff on the connection
    con.close();
    // and return the object.
    return object;
}

A zanier solution to the second case there is to use AspectJ to add a
pointcut that advises the method to get a mock ConnectionFactory instead of
doing the real getConnectionFactory call.  That technique is described here:

http://www-106.ibm.com/developerworks/java/library/j-aspectj2/?loc=j


